{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01QrRkGgErTu5zrKr9Q4WnVs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Split-horizon is working correctly. The task is complete.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe 3-member MongoDB replica set (`rs0`) is now configured with split-horizon mappings, advertising external NodePort endpoints to external clients while keeping internal cluster DNS for in-cluster members.\n\n**What I did:**\n1. Identified the topology — mongod runs with `requireTLS`, primary was `mongo-rs-2`, and the NodePort service selectors map each pod to its external endpoint:\n   - `mongo-rs-0` → `domain-rs-1:31181`\n   - `mongo-rs-1` → `domain-rs-2:31182`\n   - `mongo-rs-2` → `domain-rs-3:31183`\n2. Ran `rs.reconfig()` on the primary, adding an `external` horizon to each member with its corresponding external `hostname:nodePort`. Internal `host` values were left unchanged, and the NodePort services were not modified.\n\n**Verification** — from the `mongo-client` pod (which maps the `domain-rs-*` hostnames to the node IP), connecting to `domain-rs-1:31181` returns the external view:\n- `me = domain-rs-1:31181`\n- `hosts = [\"domain-rs-1:31181\",\"domain-rs-2:31182\",\"domain-rs-3:31183\"]`\n\nClients reaching the replica set through the external endpoints now receive the external hostnames in the `hello()` response, so the driver follows the correct split-horizon advertised addresses."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":570,"cache_read_input_tokens":45736,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":570},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0f6e136a-0eae-4a5d-8e8a-2059de5b7ffe","uuid":"e5092313-171f-47f8-9f4e-a09f7c4f5b4e","request_id":"req_011CcB3M3hFywarcCcYcjerS"}
